# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ernie-banks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The **1953 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1953.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 27, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the previous season, the postseason began with Game 1 of the 50th World Series on September 30 and ended with Game 6 on October 5.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] In the fifth iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Yankees defeated the Dodgers, four games to two, capturing their 16th championship in franchise history, concluding their 5-year World Series winning streak, an all-time record.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The 20th All-Star Game was held on July 14 at Crosley Field in Cincinnati, Ohio, home of the Cincinnati Redlegs; the National League won, 5–1.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The 1953 season had the first relocation in professional baseball since the Milwaukee Brewers moved to St.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Louis in 1902 to become the Browns, with the Boston Braves, coincidentally, relocating to Milwaukee.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] It was the first National League relocation since the St.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Maroons moved to Indianapolis and became the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] This season began a trend of relocation which would occur several times throughout the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The was also the last season for the Browns in St.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, moving east to Baltimore the following season to become the Orioles.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] On September 13, the Philadelphia Athletics became the seventh team in professional baseball to break the color line when they fielded Bob Trice; the Chicago Cubs became the eighth team just four days later when they fielded future Hall-of-Famer Ernie Banks.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] This was also the first regular season of the televised *Major League Baseball Game of the Week*, originally broadcast on ABC.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The 1953 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 13, featuring the newly relocated Milwaukee Braves and Cincinnati Reds, while American League Opening Day took place the following day, featuring six teams.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1951 that both leagues opened on different days.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the scheduled regular season was on September 27, which saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from 1946.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 30 and October 5.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] 11 tie games (5 in AL, 6 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 30 and ended on October 5 with the New York Yankees defeating the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1953 World Series in six games.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Boston Braves from Boston, Massachusetts to Milwaukee, Wisconsin as the Milwaukee Braves, they leave Braves Field (where they played 38 seasons) and move into Milwaukee County Stadium.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play there for 13 seasons through 1965 before again relocating.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns would play their last game at Busch Stadium on September 27 against the Chicago White Sox, relocating to Baltimore, Maryland at Baltimore Memorial Stadium as the Baltimore Orioles for the start of the 1954 season.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] All American League teams (except for the St.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns) signed a two-year reciprocal agreement that guaranteed the visiting team a percentage of the radio and television broadcast revenue.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The result of the Browns not signing said agreement, was that the team was shut out of the television and radio market at home and on the road.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals forged agreements with the Chicago Cubs and Cincinnati Redlegs, other teams could continue to broadcast games with opponents, even if they had not signed an agreement to do so.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Scherick approached MLB with a Saturday *Game of the Week*.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] With fewer outlets than CBS or NBC, ABC needed paid programming (or "anything for bills" as Scherick put it).
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] At first, ABC hesitated at the idea of a nationally televised regular season baseball program, but gave Scherick the green light to sign up teams.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the Sports Broadcasting Act of 1961, antitrust laws only allowed the networks to make deals with individual teams instead of pooling rights directly from a central league authority.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] Unfortunately, only three (the Philadelphia Athletics, Cleveland Indians, and Chicago White Sox were interested.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] To make matters worse, Major League Baseball barred the *Game of the Week* from airing within fifty miles of any big-league city.
[src:ernie-banks/1953-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series aired exclusively on NBC.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 22nd playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 12, 1955, at Milwaukee County Stadium, the home of the Milwaukee Braves of the National League.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The National League overcame a five-run deficit to defeat the American League, 6–5, in this edition of the midsummer classic.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Stan Musial led off the bottom of the 12th inning by drilling a home run to deep right field on the first pitch from Frank Sullivan, pulling off one of the greatest victories in All-Star Game history.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The National League began their comeback in the bottom of the seventh inning.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Willie Mays led off the frame with a single off Whitey Ford, and after two outs, Hank Aaron walked and Johnny Logan singled to drive home Mays and make it a 5–1 game.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Next batter Stan Lopata reached base on an error, and Aaron scored the second run off the inning before the third out was made.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With two outs in the eight inning, Mays, Ted Kluszewski and Randy Jackson hit consecutive singles for a run, and Ford was replaced by Sullivan.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Aaron greeted him with an RBI single scoring Kluszewski to knot the game at 5–5.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League quickly took the lead in the top of the first inning when Harvey Kuenn and Nellie Fox hit consecutive singles against Robin Roberts, with Kuenn advancing to third base from first and later scoring on a wild pitch.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Then Ted Williams walked and Mickey Mantle hit a three-run home run, before Roberts recorded his first out.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the sixth inning, Mickey Vernon grounded out to drive home Yogi Berra to give the American League a five-run cushion.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the ninth inning, Joe Nuxhall and Sullivan matched strikeouts as the All-Star Game went into extra innings for only the second time since 1950, which turned out to be the first year the game went more than nine innings.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The contest remained tied until the 12th inning, when Gene Conley struck out all three AL batters he faced.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Then came the walk-off by Musial, which was his fourth homer in All-Star games, breaking a tie with Ted Williams and Ralph Kiner.
[src:ernie-banks/1955-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was the fifth victory for the National League in the last six All-Star games, even though the American League still held a 13–9 overall advantage.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The second **1960 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 29th playing of Major League Baseball's annual midsummer exhibition game.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The game took place at Yankee Stadium in New York City, home of the American League's New York Yankees.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The National League won the game by a score of 6–0.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The National League hit four home runs, tying an All-Star Game record.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] For many local New York fans, the second All-Star Game marked the return of Willie Mays to New York.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] Against starting pitcher Whitey Ford, Mays led off the game with a single, then homered in the third.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] Eddie Mathews and Stan Musial also hit home runs in the game.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The All-Star game also marked the nineteenth and final All-Star appearance of Ted Williams, who left the competition with a .304 average, four home runs, twelve runs batted in and ten runs scored.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The **1960 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1960 season.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The 57th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that matched the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In Game 7, Bill Mazeroski hit the series winning ninth-inning home run, the first time a winner-take-all World Series game ended with a home run, and the first World Series to end on a home run.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Mazeroski's home run gave the Pirates their third title overall and their first since 1925.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Despite losing the series, the Yankees scored 55 runs, the most runs scored by any one team in World Series history, and more than twice as many as the Pirates, who scored 27.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees won three blowouts (16–3, 10–0, and 12–0), while the Pirates won four close games (6–4, 3–2, 5–2, and 10–9) to win the series.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Pirates' run differential of minus 28 is the lowest ever by any team, winner or loser, in a World Series.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Series MVP was Bobby Richardson of the Yankees, the only time in history that the award has been given to a member of the losing team, though the rules were different at this time.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Votes had to be in by the start of the 8th inning of Game 7, at which point the Yankees were in the lead, and this was the first time since the series MVP award was created in 1955 that the team leading at that point did not go on to win.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Richardson was also the first non-pitcher to be named MVP.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] This World Series featured seven past, present, or future league Most Valuable Players.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees, winners of their 10th pennant in 12 years, outscored the Pirates 55–27 in this Series, out-hit them 91–60, out-batted them .338 to .256, hit 10 home runs to Pittsburgh's four (three of which came in Game 7), got two complete-game shutouts from Whitey Ford—and lost.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Pirates' inconsistent pitching and Yankees' manager Casey Stengel's controversial decision not to start Ford in Games 1 and 4 resulted in the peculiar combination of close games and routs.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Ford (Games 3 and 6) and Vern Law (Games 1 and 4) were excellent, while Pirates relief pitcher Roy Face was a major factor in Games 1, 4 and 5.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees also committed twice as many errors as the Pirates in the series.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees had 8 errors while the Pirates had four errors.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees threw Art Ditmar against the Pirates' Vern Law (the NL Cy Young Award winner) in Game 1.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the top of the first inning, New York right fielder Roger Maris, the eventual 1960 AL MVP, drilled a home run off Law to give the Yankees a 1–0 lead.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the bottom half, however, the Pirates evened the score when Bill Virdon walked, stole second, advanced to third on an error by shortstop Tony Kubek, and scored on a double by eventual National League Most Valuable Player Dick Groat.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Bob Skinner then singled to drive in Groat and stole second, coming home on a single by Roberto Clemente.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] This was enough to compel Casey Stengel, the Yankee manager, to pull Ditmar in favor of Jim Coates, who finished the inning.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the fourth, New York cut the lead to one run when Maris singled, moved to second on a Mickey Mantle walk, took third on a fly out by Yogi Berra, and scored on a single by Bill Skowron.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] But the Pirates extended their lead to 5–2 in the fourth when Don Hoak walked and Bill Mazeroski homered.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Game 2, matching New York's Bob Turley against the Pirates' Bob Friend, saw the Yankees pummel Pittsburgh 16–3.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the top of the third, when the Yankees jumped out to a 2–0 lead.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Second baseman Bobby Richardson walked, was sacrificed over to second by Turley, and scored on a single by Tony Kubek.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Gil McDougald then doubled, plating Kubek all the way from first base.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Turley aided his own cause with an RBI single in the fourth, driving home Richardson, who had singled and moved to second on a passed ball.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Although Hoak doubled home Gino Cimoli in the bottom of the fourth to break the shutout, the Yankees extended their lead to 5–1 courtesy of a two-run home run by Mantle off Fred Green.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the sixth, the solid Yankee lead turned into a rout.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Elston Howard hit a lead-off triple and scored on Bobby Richardson's double to chase Green from the game.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] A passed ball by Smoky Burgess and error by shortstop Dick Groat on Tony Kubek's ground ball put runners on first and third with one out before McDougald's RBI single made it 7–1 Yankees.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After a walk and strikeout, Yogi Berra's two-run single and Bill Skowron's RBI single made it 10–1 Yankees.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Red Witt relieved Labine and allowed back-to-back RBI singles to Howard and Richardson that made it 12–1 Yankees.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Mantle continued the onslaught by blasting a three-run home run in the seventh off Joe Gibbon and scoring on a wild pitch by Tom Cheney in the ninth after walking and moving to third on a double, making it 16–1 Yankees.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Although the Pirates tacked on two runs in the bottom half of the frame on back-to-back RBI singles by Gino Cimoli and Smoky Burgess, Bobby Shantz relieved Turley and got Don Hoak to hit into the game-ending double play.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] This decisive Yankee victory tied the series at a game apiece.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] For Game 3, the Series shifted to Yankee Stadium as Stengel sent Whitey Ford to the mound against Pittsburgh's Vinegar Bend Mizell.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Ford had somewhat of an off year (12–9, 3.08 ERA and 192.2 IP) for his lofty standards, but was brilliant against the Pirates.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees continued the offensive onslaught they displayed in Game 2, grabbing a 6–0 lead by the end of the first inning.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After two singles, Bill Skowron drove in the first run with an RBI single.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After a walk loaded the bases, Elston Howard added another run with an RBI single off Clem Labine before Bobby Richardson capped the scoring with a grand slam (during the regular season, Richardson had hit only one home run, off Baltimore's Arnie Portocarrero on April 30).
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The next time a first inning World Series Grand slam would be hit would be in the 2021 World Series, 61 years later.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the fourth, the Bronx Bombers added on four more runs, courtesy of a two-run home run by Mickey Mantle off Fred Green and—after three singles had loaded the bases—a two-run single by Richardson off Red Witt.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Pirates, meanwhile, could not get anything going against Ford, who tossed a masterful four-hitter.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Pirates had seen their pitching fail them in the last two games, as the team fell victim to the powerful Yankee bats.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] This was not the case in Game 4, however, as Pittsburgh sent Game 1 winner Vern Law to the hill against Ralph Terry.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the bottom of the fourth, when Bill Skowron launched a home run off Law to give New York a 1–0 advantage.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The very next half-inning, though, Pittsburgh stormed back, when with two on and two outs, Law doubled in Gino Cimoli to tie the game and Bill Virdon's two-run single put the Pirates up 3–1.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Law kept the potent pinstripers at bay, though the Yankees did scratch and claw for a single run in the bottom of the seventh when Skowron doubled, moved to third on a single by McDougald, and scored on a fielder's choice on a ball hit by Richardson.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After a pinch-hit single by Johnny Blanchard, Pirate manager Danny Murtaugh brought in reliever Roy Face, who held the fort for the final 2+2⁄3 innings as Pittsburgh tied the series at two games apiece to ensure a return to Forbes Field.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] As it turned out, on this day Ditmar could not get out of the second inning once again.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Dick Stuart singled and was forced out at second on a fielder's choice hit by Gino Cimoli, who then moved to third on a double by Smoky Burgess.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then slapped a ground ball toward Yankee shortstop Tony Kubek, who flipped it to third baseman Gil McDougald in an attempt to retire Burgess, who was attempting to advance.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] However, McDougald dropped the ball for an error (Kubek's toss was accurate), allowing Cimoli to score, with Burgess safe at third, and Hoak reaching second on the error.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Bill Mazeroski then lashed a double to left, scoring Burgess and Hoak.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After this offensive outburst, Stengel yanked Ditmar and replaced him with Luis Arroyo, who finally ended the inning and stranded Mazeroski.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The next half-inning, New York picked up a run when Elston Howard doubled, moved to third on a ground-out by Bobby Richardson, and scored on another grounder by Kubek.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] However, the Pirates extended their lead back to three runs in the third, when Roberto Clemente singled home Groat, who led off with a double.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the bottom of the third, Roger Maris touched Haddix for a home run to deep right field.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Otherwise, however, the Pittsburgh hurler was in fine form, holding the Yankees at bay until the seventh, when he was replaced by Face.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the ninth, the Pirates added an insurance run off Ryne Duren.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Smoky Burgess had singled and taken second on an error; he was replaced at second by pinch-runner Joe Christopher, who moved to third on a wild pitch, and was singled in by Hoak.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Face then shut down the Yankees once again to give the Pirates a 5–2 victory and 3–2 series lead.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] For the sixth contest in Pittsburgh, the Yankees started Whitey Ford against the Pirates' Bob Friend.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] And as was the case the last time Ford had toed the rubber for the Yanks in Game 3, his teammates relentlessly mashed the ball, en route to a resounding 12–0 victory.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the top of the second, the Yankees went to work.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra walk and a Bill Skowron single, Elston Howard was hit by a pitch to load the bases (Eli Grba ran for him).
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Ford himself then notched the first RBI of the game, with a ground ball single to his counterpart Friend that scored Berra.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The next inning, after a lead-off hit-by-pitch and double, Mantle cracked a two-run single that scored Tony Kubek and Roger Maris.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra single moved Mantle to third, Pirates skipper Danny Murtaugh removed the clearly ineffective Friend in favor of Tom Cheney.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Cheney, however, fared no better, as a Bill Skowron sacrifice fly scored Mantle and, after a single, a Richardson triple to deep left field scored Berra and Johnny Blanchard, making the score 6–0.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees then ran away with the game, scoring two runs in each of the sixth, seventh, and eighth innings.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Clete Boyer hit a lead-off triple off Fred Green and scored on Kubek's single.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After another single, Berra's RBI single off Clem Labine made it 8–0 Yankees.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Next inning, after a lead-off double by Blanchard, Richardson ripped his second RBI triple of the contest, and Ford added his second RBI courtesy of a fielder's choice on a sacrifice bunt.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the eighth, Berra hit an RBI single with a runner on second, and later scored on Blanchard's double.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] As in Game 3, Ford was his masterful self, not letting the Pirates mount anything resembling a rally for the full nine innings.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] His second shutout of the series was critical, as it forced Game 7.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Yankee manager Casey Stengel would come under fire in Mickey Mantle's autobiography for letting Ford finish this game—instead of removing him once the Yankees had a comfortable lead—thus making him unavailable out of the bullpen if needed in Game 7.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] For the deciding seventh game, Bob Turley, the winning pitcher in Game 2, got the nod for the Yankees against the Pirates' Vern Law, the winning pitcher in Games 1 and 4.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Turley lasted only one inning plus one batter.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After retiring the first two batters, Turley walked Bob Skinner, then first baseman Rocky Nelson homered, Pittsburgh's first home run since Bill Mazeroski's in Game 1, to give the Pirates a 2–0 lead.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Turley was then pulled after giving up a single to Smoky Burgess leading off the second.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then drew a walk against Bill Stafford, and a bunt single by Mazeroski loaded the bases.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Stafford appeared to get the Yankees out of trouble after inducing Law to hit into a double play, pitcher to catcher to first.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] But lead-off man Bill Virdon's single to right scored Hoak and Mazeroski and increased the Pirates' lead to 4–0.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees got on the board in the fifth on Bill Skowron's lead-off home run, his second of the Series.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Bobby Richardson led off with a single and Tony Kubek drew a walk.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Elroy Face relieved Law and got Roger Maris to pop out to Hoak in foul territory, but Mickey Mantle singled to score Richardson.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Face then blew the save when Yogi Berra followed with a three-run shot to right that gave the Yankees their first lead, 5–4.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees extended their lead to 7–4 in the eighth with two more runs off Face.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] With two out, Berra walked, and Skowron singled when the Pirates couldn't get a force-out.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Johnny Blanchard (who had replaced Elston Howard at catcher for game 7) then singled to score Berra, and Clete Boyer doubled to score Skowron.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] But the Pirates retook the lead with a 5-run eighth inning.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Gino Cimoli (pinch-hitting for Face) led off with a single, and Virdon hit a ground ball to short for what could have been a double play.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] But the ball instead took a bad hop and hit Kubek in the throat, leaving everybody safe and knocking the wind out of Kubek.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] He eventually got up, and game footage showed him arguing with manager Stengel, seemingly insisting he was ok to stay in the game.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] He was eventually coaxed off the field and replaced.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] He was taken to a hospital and kept overnight for observation due to concerns surrounding his trachea swelling up and thus, causing difficulty breathing.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Back on the field, Dick Groat then chased Bobby Shantz (who had entered the game in the third and had pitched five innings, having not pitched more than four in any game during the regular season) with a single to score Cimoli and send Virdon to second.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Jim Coates relieved Shantz and got Skinner out on a sacrifice bunt, which moved the runners up.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Nelson followed with a fly ball to right, and Virdon declined to challenge Maris' throwing arm.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The high chopper allowed Virdon to score, cutting the Yankee lead to 7–6.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Hal Smith, who had replaced Smoky Burgess at catcher after being pinch-run for by Joe Christopher followed with a three-run home run to give the Pirates a 9–7 lead.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Game 4 loser Ralph Terry relieved Coates and got the last out.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Bob Friend, an 18-game winner for the Pirates and their starter (and loser) in Games 2 and 6, came on in the ninth to try to protect the lead.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson and pinch-hitter Dale Long both greeted him with singles, and Pirates manager Danny Murtaugh was forced to remove the veteran pitcher in favor of Harvey Haddix.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Although he got Roger Maris to foul out, Haddix gave up a key single to Mickey Mantle that scored Richardson and moved Long to third.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Yogi Berra followed, hitting a sharp grounder to first, with Rocky Nelson easily getting the second out.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Had Mantle been out on the play, the run would likely not have counted since the play happened so quickly that the runner on third might not have crossed the plate before the out was recorded.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] With Mantle safe, the inning continued, but ended when Bill Skowron hit into a force play.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Ralph Terry returned to the mound in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The first batter to face him was Bill Mazeroski.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] As the Pirates erupted, the Yankees stood across the field in stunned disbelief.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The improbable champions were outscored, out-hit, and outplayed, but somehow had managed to pull out a Game 7 victory.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Years later, Mickey Mantle was quoted in Ken Burns' documentary *Baseball* as saying that losing the 1960 series was the only loss, amateur or professional, he cried actual tears over.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] For Bill Mazeroski, by contrast, his Series-clinching home run was the highlight of a Hall of Fame career otherwise notable mostly for excellent defense.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Mazeroski became the first player to end the World Series with a home run.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Thirty-three years later, Joe Carter would become the only other player to end a World Series with a home run, doing so for the Toronto Blue Jays in the 1993 World Series against the Pirates' in-state rivals, the Philadelphia Phillies, albeit in Game 6.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Because of the game’s back-and-forth nature (especially in the eighth and ninth innings) and historic conclusion, the game is considered by some to be the greatest game in MLB history, as well as one of the greatest games in the history of professional sports.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Although most noted for the series-ending homer, Game 7 is also the only game in all of postseason history with no strikeouts recorded by either side.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson of the Yankees was named MVP of the Series, the only time someone from the losing team has been so honored.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] He batted .367 with 12 RBIs and eight runs in the Series and hit the key grand slam in Game 3.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Prior to the mid-1970s, television networks and stations generally did not preserve their telecasts of sporting events, choosing instead to tape over them.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] As a result, the broadcasts of the first six games are no longer known to exist.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The lone exception is a black-and-white kinescope of the entire telecast of Game 7, which was discovered in a wine cellar in Bing Crosby's former home in Hillsborough, California, in December 2009.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] A part-owner of the Pirates who was too superstitious to watch the Series live, Crosby listened to the decisive contest with his wife Kathryn and two friends on a shortwave radio in Paris, France.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Wanting to watch the game at a later date only if the Pirates won, he arranged for the telecast to be recorded by Ampex, in which he also held a financial investment.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] After viewing the kinescope, he placed it in his wine cellar, where it sat untouched for 49 years.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] It was finally found by Robert Bader, vice-president of marketing and production for Bing Crosby Enterprises, while looking through videotapes of Crosby's television specials which were to be transferred to DVD.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The five-reel set is the only known complete copy of the historic game, which was originally broadcast in color.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The NBC television announcers for the Series were Bob Prince and Mel Allen, the primary play-by-play voices for the Pirates and Yankees respectively.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Prince called the first half of Game 7 and conducted post-game interviews in the Pittsburgh clubhouse, while Allen did the latter portion of the game.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] On October 13, 2010, for the 50th anniversary of the series winning home run, a gala was hosted by the Byham Theater in downtown Pittsburgh, where the historic telecast of Game 7 was re-aired in its entirety.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] Bill Virdon, 1960 MVP Dick Groat and Yankee Bobby Richardson were guest speakers, with actor and Pittsburgh native Jeff Goldblum hosting the event.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The MLB Network would air the game and gala on December 15, 2010.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The telecast was also released on DVD by A&E Home Video.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] To date, the Pirates are the only team to win a seven-game postseason series while being out-scored by 28 runs or more.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] This would prove to be Casey Stengel's last World Series, as the Yankees soon sent him into retirement.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] This led to his famous remark, "I'll never make the mistake of turning 70 again." Mazeroski and Clemente were the last two remaining Pirates players from the 1960 World Series winners along with manager Danny Murtaugh and third-base coach Frank Oceak, when the Pirates won the World Series in 1971.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] To date, this is the last championship in any of the four major sports to be won in Pittsburgh by the home team, as the Pirates' two subsequent World Series championships in 1971 and 1979, both against the Baltimore Orioles, were clinched at Memorial Stadium.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Pittsburgh Penguins have won all five of their Stanley Cup titles on the road, and the Pittsburgh Steelers have won all six of their Super Bowl championships at neutral sites, as is customary in the NFL.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] The Yankees returned to the World Series the following year and the year after, and won back-to-back championships over the Cincinnati Reds and San Francisco Giants in five and seven games respectively.
[src:ernie-banks/1960-world-series] In 2025, the NBC radio broadcast of Game 7 by Chuck Thompson was selected by the Library of Congress for preservation in the National Recording Registry.
[src:ernie-banks/1961-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The second **1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was played in Fenway Park in Boston on July 31, 1961.
[src:ernie-banks/1961-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] It was the first MLB All-Star Game to end in a tie.
[src:ernie-banks/1961-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The Americans only got three more hits versus Sandy Koufax and Stu Miller.
[src:ernie-banks/1961-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] American starter Jim Bunning pitched three perfect innings, but Don Schwall allowed a bases-loaded single to Bill White that tied the game in the sixth.
[src:ernie-banks/1961-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] All five hits the Nationals got were charged to Schwall.
[src:ernie-banks/1961-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] Camilo Pascual pitched three shutout innings before the game was called due to rain after nine innings with the score 1–1.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The second **1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 33rd playing of Major League Baseball's annual midsummer exhibition game.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The game took place at Wrigley Field in Chicago, Illinois, home of the National League's Chicago Cubs.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The American League emerged triumphant as they finally broke out of a five-game slump with nine runs.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The nine runs equaled their total for the previous five games.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] Their victory kept the National League from tying the All-Star series at 16–16.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] The AL also had home runs by Pete Runnels, Leon Wagner and Rocky Colavito.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] A highlight of the game was the first presentation of the Arch Ward Trophy to the MVPs of each All-Star Game.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] It was first presented in 1962 as a tribute to Arch Ward, the man who founded the All-Star Game in 1933.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] That first presentation went to Leon Wagner of the Los Angeles Angels (second game MVP) and to Maury Wills of the Los Angeles Dodgers (first game MVP), because two Midsummer Classics were played.
[src:ernie-banks/1962-major-league-baseball-all-star-game-second-game] Ralph Houk's coaching staff included Hank Bauer and Bill Rigney, while Fred Hutchinson's staff included Harry Craft and Birdie Tebbetts.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1965 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 36th midseason exhibition between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and the National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was played on July 13, 1965, at Metropolitan Stadium in Bloomington, Minnesota, home of the Minnesota Twins of the American League.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in a 6–5 victory for the NL.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Traditionally, the managers of the winning pennant baseball teams of the previous year would have managed their respective leagues.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, with the firing of 1964 Yankees manager Yogi Berra, and the resignation of '64 Cardinals manager Johnny Keane (who then managed the Yankees), the second place managers (Al López of the White Sox and Gene Mauch of the Phillies) would manage their respective teams.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the National League, there had been a tie for second place, but Reds manager Fred Hutchinson had died in November 1964, making it unnecessary to break the tie.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After only five batters, the National League owned a 3–0 lead.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Willie Mays hit a leadoff home run to left field off Milt Pappas, followed by a Willie Stargell single and a two-run Joe Torre homer.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Stargell's two-run homer in the second inning off Mudcat Grant made it 5–0.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL was coasting until a four-run fifth inning against Jim Maloney, which included a pair of two-run homers by Dick McAuliffe and Harmon Killebrew, tying the game at 5-all.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The winning run scored in the seventh versus Sam McDowell on a walk to Mays, single by Hank Aaron, ground out by Roberto Clemente and infield hit by Ron Santo.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Saving the game for the NL with two innings of relief was Bob Gibson, who, with Tony Oliva in scoring position after a ninth-inning double, struck out Killebrew and Joe Pepitone to end the game.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] NL Starter Juan Marichal was named the game's MVP.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The National League roster included 14 future **Hall of Famers**.
[src:ernie-banks/1965-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League roster included 7 future **Hall of Famers**.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks is regarded as one of the greatest players of all time.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He began playing professional baseball in 1950 with the Kansas City Monarchs in the Negro leagues.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He served in the U.S. military for two years, played for the Monarchs again, and began his National League career in September 1953.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The following year, Banks was the National League Rookie of the Year runner-up.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Beginning in 1955, Banks was a National League (NL) All-Star for 11 seasons, playing in 13 of the 15 All-Star Games held during those years.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was the Cubs' main attraction in the late 1950s, the National League Most Valuable Player in 1958 and 1959, and the Cubs' first Gold Glove winner in 1960.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1962, Banks became a regular first baseman for the Cubs.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Between 1967 and 1971, he was a player-coach.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1969, through a *Chicago Sun-Times* fan poll, Cubs fans voted him the greatest Cub ever.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1970, Banks hit his 500th career home run at Wrigley Field.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He retired from playing in 1971, was a coach for the Cubs in 1972, and in 1982 was the team's first player to have his uniform number retired.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was active in the Chicago community during and after his tenure with the Cubs.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He founded a charitable organization, became the first black Ford Motor Company dealer in the United States, and made an unsuccessful bid for a local political office.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 2013, Banks was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by Barack Obama for his contribution to sports.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was born in Dallas, Texas, to Eddie and Essie Banks on January 31, 1931; he was the second of twelve children.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] His father, who had worked in construction and was a warehouse loader for a grocery chain, played baseball for black, semi-professional teams in Texas.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] As a child, Banks was not very interested in baseball, preferring swimming, basketball and football.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] His father bought him a baseball glove for less than three dollars at a five and dime store and motivated him with nickels and dimes to play catch.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] While still in high school, Banks joined the Dallas Black Giants, a semi-pro baseball team, in 1949.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] His mother encouraged him to follow one of his grandfathers into a career as a minister.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He lettered in basketball, football and track.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks' school did not have a baseball team; he played fastpitch softball for a church team during the summer.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was also a member of the Amarillo Colts, a semi-professional baseball team.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] History professor Timothy Gilfoyle wrote that Banks' talent for baseball was discovered by Bill Blair, a family friend who scouted for the Kansas City Monarchs of the Negro American League.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Other sources say Banks was noticed by Cool Papa Bell of the Monarchs.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1951, Banks was drafted into the U.S.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Army and served in Germany during the Korean War.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He served as a flag bearer in the 45th Anti-Aircraft Artillery Battalion at Fort Bliss, where he played with the Harlem Globetrotters on a part-time basis.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1953, he was discharged from the army and joined the Monarchs for the remainder of that season, achieving a .347 batting average.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks later said, "Playing for the Kansas City Monarchs was like my school, my learning, my world.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] It was my whole life." Banks hosted a program on 1450 WHFC in the late 1950s.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks signed with the Chicago Cubs in late 1953, making his major league debut on September 17 at age 22 and playing in 10 games at Wrigley Field.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was the Cubs' first black player; he became one of several former Negro league players who joined MLB teams without playing in the minor leagues.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Larry Moffi and Jonathan Kronstadt wrote that he "just was not the crusading type.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] During his first game for the Cubs, Banks received a visit from Jackie Robinson that influenced his quiet presence in baseball.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Robinson told Banks, "Ernie, I'm glad to see you're up here so now just listen and learn ...
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] For years, I didn't talk and learned a lot about people".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Later, when Banks felt like becoming more vocal, he discussed the issue with teammate Billy Williams, who advised him to remain quiet.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Williams drew the analogy of fish that are caught once they open their mouths.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks said, "I kept my mouth shut but tried to make a difference.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] My whole life, I've just wanted to make people better".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1954, Banks' double play partner during his official rookie season was Gene Baker, the Cubs' second black player.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks and Baker roomed together on road trips and became the first all-black double-play combination in major league history.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] When Steve Bilko played first base, Cubs announcer Bert Wilson referred to the Banks–Baker–Bilko double play combination as "Bingo to Bango to Bilko".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks hit 19 home runs and finished second to Wally Moon in Rookie of the Year voting.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks participated in a trend toward lighter baseball bats after he accidentally picked up a teammate's bat and liked that it was easy to generate bat speed.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1955, Banks hit 44 home runs, had 117 RBI and batted .295.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He played and was the starting NL shortstop in his first of 13 All-Star Games that season.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] His home run total was a single-season record among shortstops.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He also set a 30-year record of five single-season grand slam home runs.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks finished third in 1955 in the league's Most Valuable Player (MVP) voting, behind Roy Campanella and Duke Snider.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The Cubs finished with a 72–81 win–loss record, winning 29 of 77 road games.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1956, Banks missed 18 games due to a hand infection, breaking his run of 424 consecutive games played.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He finished the season with 28 home runs, 85 RBIs, and a .297 batting average.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He made the All-Star selection as a reserve player but did not play in the game.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1957, Banks finished the season with 43 home runs, 102 RBI, and a .285 batting average.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1958 and 1959, Banks became the first NL player to be awarded back-to-back MVP Awards, leading the league in RBI in both those seasons (with 129 and 143, respectively).
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] His 1958 season was also the first time an MVP winner was on a below-.500 team.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks hit a major-league-leading (and a career best) 47 home runs in 1958, while batting .313, third best in the NL.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The following year, he hit .304 with 45 home runs.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1959, the Cubs came the closest to a winning season since Banks' arrival, finishing with a 74–80 record.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks had a small role in an unusual play on June 30, 1959, when the St.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Louis Cardinals played the Cubs at Wrigley Field.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Stan Musial was at the plate facing Bob Anderson with a count of 3–1.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Anderson's next pitch was errant, the ball evaded catcher Sammy Taylor and rolled all the way to the backstop.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Umpire Vic Delmore called "ball four", but Anderson and Taylor contended that Musial foul tipped the ball.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Because the ball was still in play and Delmore was embroiled in an argument with Anderson and Taylor, Musial tried to run for second base.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Seeing that Musial was running to second, third baseman Alvin Dark ran to the backstop to retrieve the ball.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The ball wound up in the hands of field announcer Pat Pieper, but Dark ended up getting it back anyway.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Absentmindedly, however, Delmore pulled out a new baseball and gave it to Taylor.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] When Anderson noticed that Musial was trying for second, he took the new ball from Sammy Taylor and threw it towards Tony Taylor covering second base, and the ball went over Taylor's head into the outfield.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] At the same time that Anderson threw the new ball towards second baseman Taylor, Dark threw the original ball to shortstop Ernie Banks.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Musial did not see the throw and he was declared out when the tag was made.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1960, Banks hit a major league and NL-leading 41 HR, had 117 RBI, and led the NL in games played for the sixth time in seven years.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was also the first Cubs player to receive an annual NL Gold Glove award (for shortstop).
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1961, Banks experienced problems with a knee injury he had suffered while in the army.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] After 717 consecutive games, he removed himself from the Cubs lineup for at least four games, ending his pursuit of the record for playing in the most consecutive NL games of 895 games set by Stan Musial.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In May, the Cubs announced that Jerry Kindall would replace Banks at shortstop and that Banks would move to left field.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks later said, "Only a duck out of water could have shared my loneliness in left field".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks credited center fielder Richie Ashburn with helping him learn to play left field; in 23 games Banks committed only one error.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In June, he was moved to first base, learning that position from former first baseman and Cubs coach Charlie Grimm.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was not selected to be an All-Star for the first of two All-Star games that season since 1959, when MLB started having two All-Star Games per season through 1962, but was selected as a reserve player.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was a pinch hitter in the second All-Star game.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The Cubs began playing under the College of Coaches in 1961, a system in which decisions were made by a group of 12 coaches rather than by one manager.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] By the 1962 season, Banks hoped to return to shortstop but the College of Coaches had determined that he would remain at first base indefinitely.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In May 1962, Banks was hit in the head by a fastball from former Cubs pitcher Moe Drabowsky and was taken off the field unconscious.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He sustained a concussion, spent two nights in a hospital, sat out a Monday game, and hit three home runs and a double on Tuesday.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In May 1963, Banks set a single-game record of 22 putouts by a first baseman.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] However, he caught mumps that year and finished the season with 18 home runs, 64 RBI, and a .227 batting average.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Despite Banks' struggles that season, the Cubs had their first winning record since the 1940s.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks, following his doctor's orders, avoided his usual off-season participation in handball and basketball, and began the 1964 season weighing seven pounds (3.2 kg) more than the previous year.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks finished the season with 23 home runs, 95 RBI, and a .264 batting average.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The Cubs finished in eighth place in 1964, losing over $315,000.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1965, Banks hit 28 home runs, had 107 RBI, a .265 batting average, and played and started at first base in the All-Star Game.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] On September 2, he hit his 400th home run.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The Cubs finished the season with a baseball operations deficit of $1.2 million, though this was largely offset by television and radio revenue, and the rental of Wrigley Field to the Chicago Bears football team.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The Cubs hired Leo Durocher as manager in 1966, hoping he could inspire renewed interest in the team's fan base.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks hit only 15 home runs; Cubs finished the 1966 season in last place with a 59–103 win–loss record, the worst season of Durocher's career.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] From the time Durocher arrived in Chicago, he was frustrated at his inability to trade or bench the aging Banks.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks said of Durocher, "I wish there had been someone around like him early in my career ...
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He's made me go for that little extra needed to win".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Durocher served as Cubs manager until mid-1972, the season after Banks retired.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The Cubs appointed Banks a player-coach for the 1967 season.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks competed with John Boccabella for a starting position at first base.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Shortly after, Durocher named Banks the outright starter at first base.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks hit 23 home runs and drove in 95 runs, and went to the All-Star Game that year.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] After the 1967 season, an article in *Ebony* said Banks was not thought to have made more than $65,000 (equal to $627,620 today) in any season.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He had received a pay increase from $33,000 to $50,000 between his MVP seasons in 1958 and 1959, but *Ebony* said several MLB players were making $100,000 at the time.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks won the Lou Gehrig Memorial Award in 1968, an honor recognizing playing ability and personal character.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The 37-year-old Banks hit 32 home runs, had 83 RBI, and finished that season with a .246 batting average.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1969, he came the closest to helping the Cubs win the NL pennant; the Cubs fell from first place after holding an 8+1⁄2-game lead in August.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks made his 11th and final All-Star season appearance as a pinch hitter; it was his 14th All-Star Game appearance overall.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks hit his 500th home run on May 12, 1970, at Chicago's Wrigley Field.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] On December 1, 1971, Banks retired as a player but continued to coach for the Cubs until 1973.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was an instructor in the minor leagues for the next three seasons and also worked in the Cubs' front office.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks finished his career with 512 home runs; his 277 home runs as a shortstop were a career record at the time of his retirement.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] (Cal Ripken Jr. now holds the record for most home runs as a shortstop with 345.) Banks holds Cubs records for games played (2,528), at-bats (9,421), extra-base hits (1,009) and total bases (4,706).
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks also excelled as an infielder; he won an NL Gold Glove Award for shortstop in 1960.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He led the NL in putouts five times and was the NL leader in fielding percentage as shortstop three times, and once as first baseman.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks holds the major league record for most games played without a postseason appearance (2,528).
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In his memoir, citing his fondness for the Cubs and owner Philip K.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Wrigley, Banks said he did not regret signing with the Cubs rather than one of the more successful baseball franchises.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks' popularity and positive attitude led to the nicknames "Mr.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was known for his catchphrase, "It's a beautiful day for a ballgame ...
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Let's play two!", expressing his wish to play a doubleheader every day out of his love of baseball.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1953, after returning from military service in Germany, Banks married his first wife Mollye Ector.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He proposed to her in a letter from Germany.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Although he filed for divorce two years later, the couple briefly reconciled in early 1959.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] By that summer, they agreed on a divorce settlement that would pay $65,000 to Ector in lieu of alimony.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Shortly thereafter, Banks eloped with Eloyce Johnson.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The couple had twin sons within a year and a daughter four years after that.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Ector filed suit against Banks in 1963 for failure to make payments on a life insurance policy agreed upon in their divorce settlement.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was a lifelong Republican – and he also once stated that "I'm not goin' anywhere I'm not wanted" – prompting critics to claim that he was "soft" on Jim Crow; he ran for alderman in Chicago in 1963.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He ran in the 8th Ward against Democratic incumbent James A.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] 26 primary, Banks finished a distant third, garnering just 12% of the vote (Condon won re-election with 55%; Gerald Gibbons drew 25%).
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He later said, "People knew me only as a baseball player.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] They didn't think I qualified as a government official and no matter what I did I couldn't change my image ...
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] What I learned, was that it was going to be hard for me to disengage myself from my baseball life and I would have to compensate for it after my playing days were over." Banks endorsed George W.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1966, Banks worked for Seaway National Bank in the off-season and enrolled in a banking correspondence course.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He bought into several business ventures, including a gas station, during his playing career.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Though he had been paid modestly in comparison to other baseball stars, Banks had taken the advice of Wrigley and invested much of his earnings.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He later spent time working for an insurance company and for New World Van Lines.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks began building assets that would be worth an estimated $4 million by the time he was 55 years old.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks and Bob Nelson became the first black owners of a U.S.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Ford Motor Company dealership in 1967, Ernie Banks Ford on Chicago's south side.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Nelson had been the first non-white commissioned officer in the United States Army Air Forces during World War II; he operated an import car dealership before the venture with Banks.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was appointed to the board of directors of the Chicago Transit Authority in 1969.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] On a trip to Europe, Banks visited the Pope, who presented him with a medal that became a prized possession.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] She received several valuable items from his playing career as part of their divorce settlement, including his 500th home run ball.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] She sold the items not long after the divorce.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1993, his third wife Marjorie was part of a group that met with MLB executives to discuss race relations in baseball after allegations of racial slurs surfaced against Cincinnati Reds owner Marge Schott.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks married Liz Ellzey in 1997 and Hank Aaron served as his best man.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In late 2008, Banks and Ellzey adopted an infant daughter.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks's nephew, Bob Johnson, was a major league catcher and first baseman for the Texas Rangers between 1981 and 1983.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] His great nephew, Acie Law, is a professional basketball player who attended Texas A&M University before playing in the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1969, Banks had been appointed to the Chicago Transit Board (the Chicago Transit Authority's governing and administrative body) by the governor of Illinois.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He would continue to serve on the board until 1981.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks served as a team ambassador after his retirement, though author Phil Rogers says the team had never placed Banks in a position of authority or significant influence.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1983, shortly after Wrigley sold the team to the Tribune Company, Banks and the Cubs briefly severed ties.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Rogers wrote that after the sale, Banks was viewed as "something of a crazy uncle who hung around the house for no apparent reason", and that team officials anonymously told the press that Banks had been fired because he was unreliable.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] At the time, he was employed as the Cubs' corporate sales representative.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Soon Banks and the Cubs reconciled and he resumed making appearances on behalf of the team.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 1984, when the Cubs won the NL East division, the club named Banks an honorary team member.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] At the 1990 Major League Baseball All-Star Game, the first one held at Wrigley Field since Banks' playing days, he threw out the ceremonial first pitch to starting catcher Mike Scioscia.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 2003, he guest starred on an episode of *Yes, Dear*.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In June 2006, *Crain's Chicago Business* said Banks was part of a group looking into buying the Chicago Cubs in case the Tribune Company decided to sell the club.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks established a charity, the Live Above & Beyond Foundation, which assists youth and the elderly with issues including self-esteem and healthcare.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 2008, Banks released a charity wine called Ernie Banks 512 Chardonnay, the proceeds of which were donated to his foundation.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was an ordained minister; he presided at the wedding of MLB pitcher Sean Marshall.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] On March 31, 2008, a statue of Banks (*Mr.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Cub*) was unveiled in front of Wrigley Field.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] That year, Eddie Vedder released a song called "All The Way", which Banks had asked Vedder to write about the Cubs as a birthday gift.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks remained close to the Cubs team and made frequent appearances at their spring training grounds, HoHoKam Stadium in Arizona.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Author Harry Strong wrote in 2013 that "the Chicago Cubs do not have a mascot, but they hardly need one when the face of the franchise is still so visible".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks died of a heart attack at a Chicago hospital on January 23, 2015, eight days before his 84th birthday.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Following a public visitation, a memorial service was held at the Fourth Presbyterian Church.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Several well-known people spoke at the service, including Chicago mayor Rahm Emanuel and baseball personalities Joe Torre and Billy Williams.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] After the service, a procession moved from Downtown Chicago past Wrigley Field.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In the weeks after his death, a legal battle arose over Banks' estate and the disposition of his body.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] His estranged widow Elizabeth said that he had amended his will in October without her knowledge.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The new will left all of Banks' assets to his longtime caregiver, Regina Rice.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks had been diagnosed with dementia shortly before the change in his will.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] A Chicago funeral home sent Elizabeth a bill for $35,000 in funeral costs, but the bill went unpaid as Elizabeth challenged the legality of Banks' new will.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In March 2015, the Chicago Cubs announced that they would pay the funeral home costs.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was buried in Graceland Cemetery, near Wrigley Field, beneath a monument that pay tribute to his sports and public career.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] During the entire 2015 season, the Cubs had the number 14 located behind home plate.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was voted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame in 1977, his first year of eligibility.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He received votes on 321 of the 383 ballots.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Though several players were selected through the Veterans Committee and the Special Committee on the Negro Leagues that year, Banks was the only player elected by the Baseball Writers' Association of America.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was inducted on August 8 of that year.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The Cubs retired Banks' uniform number 14 in 1982.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was the first player to have his number retired by the team.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] The team did not retire any more numbers for another five years, when Billy Williams received the honor.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Through the 2023 season only six former Cubs, along with Brooklyn Dodger Jackie Robinson, have had their numbers retired by the organization.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] Banks was named to the Major League Baseball All-Century Team in 1999.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] That same year, *The Sporting News* ranked him number 38 on its list of "Baseball's 100 Greatest Players".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 2020, *The Athletic* ranked Banks at number 65 on its "Baseball 100" list, complied by sportswriter Joe Posnanski.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 2022, as part of their SN Rushmore project, *The Sporting News* named Banks on their "Chicago Mount Rushmore of Sports", along with Chicago Bulls basketball player Michael Jordan, Chicago Bears football player Walter Payton, and Chicago Blackhawks hockey player Bobby Hull.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] He was inducted as a Laureate of The Lincoln Academy of Illinois and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State's highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 1970, in the area of Sports.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 2009, Banks was named a Library of Congress Living Legend, a designation that recognizes those "who have made significant contributions to America's diverse cultural, scientific and social heritage".
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] In 2013, he received the Presidential Medal of Freedom with 15 other people, including Bill Clinton and Oprah Winfrey.
[src:ernie-banks/ernie-banks] During the ceremony, he presented President Obama with a bat that had belonged to Jackie Robinson.
